# Rule 1 — Velocity over compatibility

This project optimizes for **speed of delivery**. Treat this as the top constraint in every change.

## Non-negotiables

- **No legacy methods**: Do not introduce or preserve deprecated APIs, compatibility shims, or “we support both old and new” patterns in first-party code.
- **Breaking changes are allowed**: Prefer clean, modern interfaces. Remove obsolete entry points, flags, and indirection instead of layering adapters to keep old behavior alive.
- **Delete over wrap**: When replacing behavior, remove the old implementation rather than keeping it “just in case.”
- **No quality shortcuts**: Velocity is not an excuse to bypass quality checks (e.g. disabling eslint rules, suppressing lint/type errors, or similar cheats) to force a change through.

## Scope and definitions

- **Scope**: This rule applies to first-party runtime code and contracts in `fe/` and `be/`, including DTOs, API payloads, persisted JSON keys, and shared app-facing types.
- **Compatibility layer**: Any code whose main purpose is to accept, translate, or maintain both an old and new contract shape for callers you control.
- **Dual code path**: Two implementations of the same app behavior kept active in parallel for compatibility reasons.
- **Migration exception**: Time-bounded DB/schema transitions are allowed only when they include an explicit removal follow-up in the same change.
- **Out of scope**: Third-party dependency deprecations are handled by dependency upgrade work, not by adding new local compatibility wrappers.

## Exception policy

- Backward compatibility is out of scope by default.
- Allow compatibility work only when the user explicitly requests it in the same task and names both the consumer and removal horizon.
- Without that explicit request, delete old paths immediately instead of preserving adapters.

## For the agent

- Default to the **current** canonical approach for the stack (framework APIs, module layout, config shape).
- If a choice is “safe for old callers” vs “simpler for new code,” choose **simpler for new code** unless told otherwise.
- Do not block refactors with hypothetical external consumers; this repo accepts breakage.
- Treat “velocity” as permission for clean breaking changes, not permission to weaken guardrails.
- Reject requests to keep legacy fields “just in case” unless the user provides a concrete compatibility scope and removal date.
- For UI polish tasks, prefer low-effort reuse of existing patterns (especially mobile-first layouts) and avoid broad desktop redesigns unless explicitly requested.
